# MVI Patterns

## Store (api)

```kotlin
interface {Feature}Store : Store<Intent, State, Label> {

    data class State(
        val someValue: String = "",
        val isLoading: Boolean = false,
        val isError: Boolean = false,
    )

    sealed interface Intent {
        data class OnValueChange(val newValue: String) : Intent
        data object SomeAction : Intent
    }

    sealed interface Label {
        data object NavigateToNext : Label
    }
}
```

- State — always `data class`, never `sealed`
- Intent and Label — always `sealed interface`

## Executor (impl)

Extends `BaseExecutor` (from `core-mvikotlin`), **not** `CoroutineExecutor` directly.
Logic goes in `suspendExecuteIntent` / `suspendExecuteAction` — already wrapped in `scope.launch` by `BaseExecutor`.

**State access rules:**
- **Before** async operation — save `state()` to a local variable for guard clauses
- **After** async operation — always call fresh `state()`, it may have changed during the request

```kotlin
internal class {Feature}Executor(
    mainDispatcher: CoroutineDispatcher,
) : BaseExecutor<Intent, Nothing, State, Message, Label>(mainContext = mainDispatcher) {

    override suspend fun suspendExecuteIntent(intent: Intent) {
        when (intent) {
            is Intent.OnValueChange -> dispatch(Message.SetValue(intent.newValue))
            Intent.SomeAction -> publish(Label.NavigateToNext)
        }
    }
}
```

## Reducer (impl)

```kotlin
internal class {Feature}Reducer : Reducer<State, Message> {

    override fun State.reduce(msg: Message): State = when (msg) {
        is Message.SetValue -> copy(someValue = msg.value)
    }
}
```

## StoreFactory (impl)

`Message` is declared as `internal sealed interface` inside `StoreFactory`:

```kotlin
internal class {Feature}StoreFactory(
    private val storeFactory: StoreFactory,
    private val mainDispatcher: CoroutineDispatcher,
) {

    fun create(): {Feature}Store =
        object :
            {Feature}Store,
            Store<Intent, State, Label> by storeFactory.create(
                name = {Feature}Store::class.simpleName,
                initialState = State(),
                bootstrapper = null,
                executorFactory = { {Feature}Executor(mainDispatcher) },
                reducer = {Feature}Reducer()
            ) {}

    internal sealed interface Message {
        data class SetValue(val value: String) : Message
    }
}
```

## BaseViewModel (presentation)

`BaseViewModel` (from `core-presentation`) extends `ViewModel()` and exposes iOS-compatible flow wrappers from moko-mvvm:
- `state: CStateFlow<State>` — collected with `collectAsStateWithLifecycle()` on Android
- `label: CFlow<Label>` — one-time events via `OneTimeEvent` (buffered `Channel<T>`)

`bindAndStart { }` wires store flows to ViewModel state/label inside `init`.

```kotlin
class {Feature}ViewModel internal constructor(
    private val store: {Feature}Store,
    private val stateMapper: Ui{Feature}StateMapper,
    private val labelMapper: Ui{Feature}LabelMapper,
) : BaseViewModel<Ui{Feature}State, Ui{Feature}Label>(initialState = Ui{Feature}State()) {

    init {
        bindAndStart {
            store.states.mapNotNull(stateMapper::map) bindTo ::acceptState
            store.labels.mapNotNull(labelMapper::map) bindTo ::acceptLabel
        }
    }

    fun onValueChange(value: String) = store.accept(Intent.OnValueChange(value))
    fun onSomeAction() = store.accept(Intent.SomeAction)

    override fun onCleared() {
        super.onCleared()
        store.dispose()
    }
}
```

## Screen (ui)

Labels (one-time events) are collected with `CollectFlow`. State is collected with `collectAsStateWithLifecycle()`:

```kotlin
@Composable
internal fun {Feature}Screen(
    onNavigateToNext: () -> Unit,
    viewModel: {Feature}ViewModel = koinViewModel(),
) {
    val state by viewModel.state.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()

    viewModel.label.CollectFlow { label ->
        when (label) {
            Ui{Feature}Label.NavigateToNext -> onNavigateToNext()
        }
    }

    // UI content using state
}
```

Use `CollectFlowWithLifecycle` instead of `CollectFlow` when lifecycle-aware collection is needed.
